      <h2 id="best-budget">Best Budget: Crucial X9 Portable SSD</h2>
      <p>If you want Samsung T7 speeds without the T7 price, the Crucial X9 is the strongest budget alternative at roughly two-thirds the cost. According to manufacturer specifications, it delivers 1050 MB/s read and 1000 MB/s write, within 5% of the T7 on benchmark performance. For pure speed-per-dollar, it is excellent.</p>
      <p>The tradeoffs are security and build. There is no fingerprint scanner, only software AES encryption you must set up manually, and the plastic body means heat builds up faster — published specifications indicate a potential 15% speed drop in the later stages of large transfers as the drive warms. The warranty is three years versus Samsung's five. For non-sensitive backups and occasional large file transfers, the X9 is a smart value. For daily use with sensitive data and a rough commute, the T7's aluminum body and fingerprint lock justify the premium.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide</h2>
      <p>The first decision is capacity, and the rule is to buy 50% more than you currently need. Storage demands grow faster than people expect — a 500GB drive that feels spacious today will be full in a year if you start shooting video or running full system images. For document and photo backups, 500GB is the floor. For video editing or full system images, 1TB is the practical minimum. 2TB makes sense if you archive raw video or maintain multiple dated full-system backups. Price per GB drops significantly at the 1TB tier, so it is usually worth the jump from 500GB.</p>
      <p>Speed ratings are misleading if you only look at peak numbers. Manufacturers quote maximum burst speeds achieved into the drive's cache, but sustained speeds after the cache fills are what matter for real backups. Look for reviews that test sustained writes over 50GB or more. NVMe-based drives in aluminum enclosures (like the T7) sustain speed because the metal dissipates heat; plastic-bodied drives often throttle by 20-40% after a minute of continuous writes. If your backups are small, this does not matter. If you back up hundreds of gigabytes at once, it is the difference between a 5-minute job and a 15-minute job.</p>
      <p>Finally, consider security. If the drive lives on your desk, software encryption is fine. If it travels in a bag with sensitive data, hardware encryption with a fingerprint or PIN is worth paying for — software encryption can be bypassed if someone has your laptop password, but hardware encryption on a locked drive is effectively unbreakable without the biometric or PIN. The Samsung T7's fingerprint model costs slightly more than the standard T7, and for anyone who travels with client or financial data, that premium is justified.</p>
      <p>Learn more about our <a href="/how-we-test/">evaluation methodology</a> and <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>Is an external SSD better than an external HDD for backup?</summary>
          <p>Yes, for active use. SSDs are 5-10x faster, more drop-resistant, and smaller. HDDs still win on cost per terabyte for cold archive storage of large media libraries you rarely access. For daily backups and working files, an SSD is worth the premium.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Do I need 500GB, 1TB, or 2TB of external storage?</summary>
          <p>For document and photo backups, 500GB is plenty. For video editing or full system images, 1TB is the practical minimum. 2TB makes sense if you archive raw video or keep multiple full system backups. Buy 50% more capacity than you currently need to avoid upgrading in a year.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Does the Samsung T7 fingerprint scanner work reliably?</summary>
          <p>According to Samsung's product documentation, the fingerprint sensor unlocks on the first try roughly 90% of the time, similar to a phone fingerprint sensor. You can register multiple fingers, and a PIN fallback works if your finger is wet or the sensor fails. The fingerprint adds real security for a drive you carry in a bag.</p>
        </details>
      </div>

